-- France Stocks Decline: Total, Sanofi-Aventis, PPR Lead CAC 40's Retreat
-- David Altaner
-- 2010-07-01T16:01:02Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-01/dexia-faurecia-gdf-gecina-natixis-partouche-french-equity-preview.html

          
          
             France’s benchmark CAC 40 Index fell
102.99, or 3 percent, to 3,339.9, the lowest close in five
weeks. The SBF 120 Index declined 2.9 percent.  
 The following were among the most active stocks traded in
France today.  
 Groupe Partouche SA  (PARP FP) dropped 2.7 percent to 2.18
euros. The French casino company reported net income of 5.9
million euros ($7.3 million) for the first six months of its
fiscal year and said it remains “cautious” on its full-year
earnings forecast.  
 PPR SA  (PP FP) declined 4.3 percent to 98.10 euros. The
owner of the Gucci luxury goods brand was downgraded to
“neutral” from “overweight” at JPMorgan Chase & Co.  
 Sanofi-Aventis SA  (SAN FP) fell 2.6 percent to 48.23 euros.
France’s largest drugmaker was removed from a list of “top
picks” at Barclays Plc.  
 Total SA  (FP FP) declined 2.9 percent to 35.88 euros.
Europe’s biggest refiner said a ruling by an appeal court in
northern France forcing it to restart operations at its Dunkirk
plant won’t affect its plan to close the facility.  
 Separately, crude oil fell for a fourth day in New York,
the longest losing streak in seven weeks.  
